25|$|Some unorthodox economists like Stephen Kanitz {{attribute}} {{the debt crisis}} not to the high Brazilian level of indebtedness nor to the disorganization of the country's economy. They say {{that the cause of}} the crisis was rather a minor error in the U.S. government <b>banking</b> <b>regulations</b> which forbids its banks from lending over ten times the amount of their capital, a regulation that, when the inflation eroded their lending limits, forced them to cut the access of underdeveloped countries to international savings.|$|E
